The thing is, while I get the gist of the poem, the language doesn't sit well with me. The guy was writing this in 1890 - why the thee's and thy's? In Polish it's considered a major literary faux pas to use antiquated language: it's seen as cheap and effete. Apparently that's not the case with poetry in English (maybe because these olden forms work better with metered verses?), yet my brain is Polish: I can't abandon thought patterns I've been learning for decades.

I appreciate what you're trying to achieve but I'm afraid I'm a lost cause - too Polish in my head.

@dutchiris

Also, each time I encounter a non-standard word in writing I experience what might be described as a mental stutter - my eyes don't just glide over the word with my mind getting the meaning instantly: there is a tiny delay. Betwixt, thee, etc. - I stumble for a microsecond on each of those, and the effect is quite unpleasant. The rhythm is lost, and so is my concentration.

You know English on a completely differently level than I do, and you've had a lifetime of experiencing poetry in the language. What comes naturally to you either does not come to me, at all, or if it does then with much more effort.

@dutchiris

That's my point, really. When it comes to poetry, my English is that of a child (as was Abe's apparently). But I'm OK with it. As a young man I used to strive to be good at everything and it never brought me any joy. In middle age I have learned to embrace my shortcomings. Is that a faux pas? 

